Listeriosis - France: background 20000220192206
Date: Sat, 26 Feb 2000 14:18:23 -0500
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media, 26 Feb 2000 [edited

Health officials have discovered three new cases of listeri[osis in
France, bringing to 26 the number of people who have been [infected by the
bacterium since outbreaks began in November.
In a statement released late Friday, the Health Ministry said the National
Listeria Center had found two elderly people and a newborn infant suffering
from listeriosis.
The statement also said the three newest cases were likely caused by the
consumption of tainted pork tongue in gelatin. Authorities have said that
pork tongue is likely at the root of the epidemic, though they have not yet
isolated the specific factory where the meat was produced.
Seven people have died of listeria poisoning in France since outbreaks
started in November.
